posts.name: Lexeo
posts.cooked: My High school had a printer similar to this. The nice thing is that it seemed relatively easy to use and it worked really well with the soluble support material. The down side is the material is EXTREMELY expensive (like $180/spool), and you are limited to their material only. I would say these are great machines to have for companies, but the cost is limiting for FRC. I’d say selling the machine is not a great look, and pretty unGP, so I think we will probably avoid entering that “lottery”. Lulzbots and Prusas will continue to be our goto.

posts.name: Christopher Ely
posts.cooked:
We have a Stratasys FDM printer. The current model is a Fortus series, but we have had two Dimension 1200es’ before this one.

Pros:

Part quality is generally excellent.

Can print soluble support material.

Cons:

Material is expensive.

Soluble support removal requires a heated, high pH, detergent bath.

We had reliability issues with our Dimension. I think the issue was with the hard drive and/or power supply.

posts.name: Lexeo
posts.cooked:
True, however with a Markforged, you are getting Carbon fiber mixed with nylon. With this printer you are getting ABS. Most teams are going to benefit from a “cheap to use printer” like a Prusa or Ender 3 in addition a Markforged for proof of concepts.

For most FRC applications, teams are going to find PETG or PLA+ a better material than ABS from a strength/functionality perspective.

posts.name: Nelson Green (1108 Mentor Coach Electrical Programming)
posts.cooked:
I didn’t think this was worth a whole thread but I’m excited about a $50 automation direct voucher.

I’m a little uncertain about the low number of vouchers it seems though.  At least this round the Adobe products vouchers didn’t return.

It is interesting see both gear and pulley stock.  Though we haven’t always been really great at parting out on the lathe, I think their is a 3/4 hub stock nearby.  I’d have to think where we’d use those.

I’m less down on the network switch, I’m glad they have one in FC even if not exact model of 900 doc it is a better option than not for onboard processors.

The Andymark AM14U axle nut holders are nice to have in FC.

100 credits for a NEO without a Spark Max seems a little much to me.  Wonder if that is a round 2 item.  Also maybe that should have flipped (aka grab a spark max, then use your voucher to buy a motor).
